AGI - Despite the great progress in Brazil and Colombia, the process of deforestation > of the rainforest has progressed at a constant pace in 2023. According to the data of the World Resources Institute, or WRI, and the University of Maryland, last year an area of unspoilt rainforests, extended almost as much as Switzerland, for a total of 37,000 square km>, was completely erased by human activity. The loss proceeds at a rate of ten football fields per minute, due to the expansion of agriculture. While Brazil and Colombia have recorded a sharp decline in forest loss, respectively 36% and 49%, thanks to the environmental policies of Presidents Luiz Inàcio Lula da Silva and Gustavo Petro, these losses have been compensated by strong increases in Bolivia, Laos, Nicaragua and other countries. Canada also recorded a record forest disappearance due to fires, losing more than 8 million hectares.
&nbsp;
"The world has taken two steps back and forth with regard to the loss of forests this year," said Mikaela Weisse, Director of the WRI Global Forest Watch.
&nbsp;
"The strong decreases in Amazonia in Brazil and Colombia show that progress is possible, but the increase in forest loss in other areas largely blocked such progress," said Weisse. "We must learn from countries that are successfully slowing down deforestation," Weisse continued. Changes in land use that cause deforestation, such as agricultural practices, are the second source of greenhouse gas emissions and one of the main factors of biodiversity loss.> According to researchers, rainforest conservation is essential to limit global warming to 1.5 C, > compared to pre-industrial levels. According to scientists, the fact that deforestation is continuing at record pace indicates that governments are dangerously off-road in climate and biodiversity.
&nbsp;
At the conference on the climate 'Cop28' in Dubai, > governments agreed on the need to stop and reverse the loss and degradation of forests by 2030>, after the commitment of world leaders to 'Cop26' in Glasgow to end their destruction by this decade. But the new data shows that the world is far from achieving this goal, with few changes in global forest loss for several years. Although Brazil has significantly slowed its rate of forest loss, the country has remained one of the first three for the disappearance of primary rainforests, along with the Democratic Republic of the Congo and Bolivia. Together, they reached more than half of the total destruction of forests globally. For the third consecutive year, Bolivia has recorded a surge in the loss of forests, although it has less than half of the forests of other important rain countries, such as the Democratic Republic of the Congo and Indonesia, mainly because of the expansion of soy cultivation.
&nbsp;
Laos and Nicaragua have lost most of their pristine rainforest in 2023, with a deforestation of 1.9% and 4.2% respectively in one year; According to researchers, this is due to the fact that highly fragmented forests in already widely dispersed countries can often be erased faster. In Laos, agricultural expansion is fueled by China's demand for raw materials, while in Nicaragua the blame is on growing livestock and agriculture. Despite the lack of overall progress in figures for 2023, experts stressed that the world could learn from examples of Brazil and Colombia to achieve deforestation goals. "I really believe that the only way to keep the forests standing is a compensation fund for the conservation of rainforests," said Matthew Hansen, a remote sensing specialist at the geography department of the University of Maryland.
&nbsp;
"Germany has proposed the 'Fair Deal', which aims to finance countries living in rainforests," Hansen said. "Norway has committed itself to Gabon in a similar way, using carbon sequestration as a measure," Gabon added. "If a solid governance and civil society's commitment to this approach, the forest recovery plan could work," said Hansen.&nbsp;
